etymologies: mid 18th century (originally in nautical use): of unknown origin

definitions: turn or slide violently or uncontrollably in a particular direction

examples.text: the Chevy slewed from side to side in the snow
he managed to slew the aircraft around before it settled on the runway

shortDefinitions: turn or slide violently or uncontrollably

definitions: a violent or uncontrollable sliding movement

examples.text: I was assaulted by the thump and slew of the van

definitions: a large number or quantity of something

examples.text: he asked me a slew of questions

shortDefinitions: large number or quantity of something

etymologies: Old English slēan ‘strike, kill’, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch slaan and German schlagen

definitions: kill (a person or animal) in a violent way
shortDefinitions: kill person or animal in violent way

examples.text: a man was slain with a shotgun
you slay me, you really do

definitions: be extremely impressive, stylish, or successful
shortDefinitions: be extremely impressive, stylish, or successful
